                    "comment": "nealrichardson commented on pull request #6517: ARROW-7984: [R] Check for valid inputs in more places \nURL: https://github.com/apache/arrow/pull/6517\n \n \n   This follows some of the test refactoring in #6488 and protects against more bad inputs. Some questions that arise:\r\n   \r\n   * Sending an `offset` to `Array::Slice` that is out of bounds causes a crash (in a debug build at least). That should probably error instead.\r\n   * Sending a `length` to `Array::Slice` that is too large doesn't error, but it does seem to only return the valid data (i.e. it doesn't keep reading memory outside the array to give you the length you requested). That would make sense to me if the argument were called `limit` (as in, give me up to this many values), but since it's called `length` that sounds like it should error (https://github.com/apache/arrow/blob/master/cpp/src/arrow/array.h#L212-L213)\r\n   * Many methods that take an integer index (e.g. `ChunkedArray::chunk`) don't validate that the index is valid, so they crash on negative or too large integers. I added some checks for this in the R bindings, but shouldn't this happen in the C++ library?\r\n   \r\n   I wasn't sure if there was a reason we don't validate these inputs in the C++ library. (Performance? but surely it's cheap to check whether an integer is non-negative) \r\n   \r\n   cc @pitrou @bkietz \n \n----------------------------------------------------------------\nThis is an automated message from the Apache Git Service.\nTo respond to the message, please log on to GitHub and use the\nURL above to go to the specific comment.\n \nFor queries about this service, please contact Infrastructure at:\nusers@infra.apache.org\n",
